	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Mac might have been SCSI? I don't know how early they grew the external SCSI port.<br /></div><br />Our entry level scanner only supported serial and (bi-directional) parallel ports. Note that they didn't release two separate products for the two platforms, but actually included the software for both in one package, and it's obviously costly to have a (relatively) cheap device supporting three different methods of connection, so there was no SCSI and MAC users would connect it via a parallel port. SCSI was so uncommon on PCs at that time anyway.<br /><br />I'm not sure but I think the more expensive models might support both parallel and SCSI ports (but not serial), so that PC users could use parallel (the card was included anyway) and MAC users could choose from either (though SCSI was probably preferred).<br /><br />Even more ironic was that, our PC actually had SCSI in it for some reasons.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


