	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The earliest of Macs—apparently the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macintosh_Plus" class="postlink">Mac Plus</a> was the first with SCSI—used the same DB25 connector as the PC for the parallel port.<br /><br />The pinout is substantially different—<a href="http://antinode.info/mac/scsi_25.html" class="postlink">DB25 SCSI</a> vs <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_port#Pinouts" class="postlink">Centronics</a>—but they're both 8-bit parallel buses with a 9 control signals. It's conceivable that it was practical to implement support for both pinouts... maybe.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

